# Breaking Things to Build Myself: My Internship at Golden Suntec Solutions

> *Three months of pipelines, ERP systems, client data, and a lot of trial and error — here's what I built, what I broke, and what I learned along the way.*

**Author:** John David Gayagoy
**Date:** May 2026
**Tags:** ERP · Software Dev · Data Engineering · Marketing · Golden Suntec Solutions

---

## Walking into a world I didn't fully understand

When I joined Golden Suntec Solutions Inc., I knew I was stepping into something bigger than I'd experienced before. A company that builds and implements Odoo — a full-scale ERP system — as its core product. On day one, I realized quickly that the gap between knowing software and understanding enterprise business systems was wider than I'd expected.

Odoo wasn't just an app. It was an entire ecosystem — modules for accounting, inventory, CRM, HR, and more, all woven together. Understanding it wasn't just a technical challenge; it was a business one. And honestly? I'm still learning it. But three months in, I now have enough knowledge and hands-on expertise to do real, meaningful work — and that in itself felt like a major win.

---

## Building odoo-data-flow: a pipeline that actually mattered

My flagship project was **odoo-data-flow** — a structured 3-stage data import pipeline designed to migrate large external client datasets into Odoo via JSON-RPC. This wasn't a toy project. Our clients had real, complex data that needed to land accurately inside a live ERP system.

| Metric | Result |
|---|---|
| Data migration speed | **80% faster** |
| Import pipeline stages | **3 structured stages** |
| Schema mismatch errors | **Significantly reduced** |

### Key deliverables

- **Configurable CLI wrapper** — Built a command-line tool that streamlined execution across environments, reducing setup time and boosting developer productivity significantly.

- **Automated bulk record insertion** — Added validation checks that caught schema mismatches before they hit the database, dramatically reducing import failures and improving data accuracy for clients.

- **Client-facing data handling** — Transformed large-scale, messy business datasets from real clients into clean, structured records ready for Odoo — learning that data is never as clean as you hope.

---

## The hardest part? Understanding what the data even meant

The biggest technical challenge wasn't the code — it was making sense of large-scale business data from clients who each had their own formats, naming conventions, and quirks. Transforming that into something Odoo could digest without breaking required not just engineering skills, but business understanding too.

And then there was Odoo itself. As an ERP system built to handle virtually every business function, onboarding with it felt like trying to learn a city by walking every street at once. There were moments of genuine confusion. But those moments taught me more than the smooth days ever did.

> *"The best way to learn things is by breaking things."*
> — Sir Jim

That quote from Sir Jim stuck with me throughout. Every time something broke in the pipeline, every failed import, every schema mismatch — those weren't setbacks. They were lessons delivered fast.

---

## The tools and mindset I'm taking with me

Beyond the project deliverables, I came away with a stack of real-world tools and capabilities I didn't have before:

| Tool / Skill | What I learned |
|---|---|
| **Odoo ERP** | Practical knowledge of a full enterprise platform, from modules to APIs |
| **Docker** | Containerizing apps for consistent, portable environments |
| **Kubernetes** | Orchestrating containers at scale in production environments |
| **n8n** | Building workflow automations that connect systems and reduce manual work |
| **Ubuntu / Linux** | Working comfortably in a Linux environment for development and deployment |
| **Data Pipelines** | Designing end-to-end flows for importing, validating, and transforming data |

---

## What I'd tell anyone starting their first real tech role

Don't wait to feel ready. I spent some of my early weeks hoping I'd wake up one day just "getting" Odoo. That day didn't come on its own — I had to go out and break things until they started making sense. That's how real learning works, especially in tech.

Ask questions even when they feel basic. Build things even when you're not sure they'll work. And when something breaks, sit with it long enough to understand why — because that's where the real knowledge lives.

---

My internship at Golden Suntec Solutions Inc. gave me more than a list of tools and technologies. It gave me a way of thinking — curious, persistent, and unafraid of breaking things in pursuit of building something better. I'm carrying that into everything I do next.
